{"title_page": "Carcara UAV", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name = Carcar\u00e1\n |image = FotosCarcara.jpg\n |caption =\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n |type = [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|UAV]]\n |manufacturer = [[SantosLab]]\n |designer =\n |first flight = 2009\n |introduction =  \n |retired =\n |number built = \n |status = Active\n |unit cost = \n |primary user = [[Brazilian Navy]]  \n |more users =  \n |variants with their own articles =  Carcara II\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Carcar\u00e1''' is a Brazilian light weight [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] designed to be transported by a single soldier. The soldier's height allows takeoff and landing in restricted areas where other aircraft are unable to operate. It is designed to be used in any theater even if it is without roads or paths, or surrounded by obstacles.\n\nIt is designed to be used by [[Brazilian Marine Corps]] infantry in real-time reconnaissance.\n \n==Characteristics==\n\nThe Carcar\u00e1 was ordered by the [[Brazilian Navy]] to equip an infantry [[Brazilian Marine Corps|Marine Corps]]. The Navy wanted a [[UAV]] with[[Stealth technology | stealth]] features which was lightweight, flexible and resistant. The Carcar\u00e1 has a low acoustic signature, can be controlled by a single soldier and can gather telemetry data. It can be programmed to follow a target automatically. To the naked eye while in the air, it is very similar to a [[Caracara (subfamily)|caracara]].\n\n==Specifications==\n*Wingspan: 160&nbsp;cm\n*Operating speed: 40&nbsp;km / h\n*Takeoff: manual or catapult\n*Recovery: \"deep stall\"\n*Autonomy: 60 to 95 minutes\n*Payload: mobile camera with zoom, or Infra-red sensor\n\n==External links==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20091202073024/http://www.uav.com.br/carcara.htm\n* http://www.defesanet.com.br/01_lz/laad2009/imagens/mb/carcara_vant.jpg\n\n[[Category:2000s Brazilian military aircraft]]\n[[Category:Unmanned aerial vehicles of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Unmanned military aircraft of Brazil]]\n\n\n{{UAV-stub}}\n{{aero-2000s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name = Carcar\u00e1\n |image = FotosCarcara.jpg\n |caption =\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n |type = [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|UAV]]\n |manufacturer = [[SantosLab]]\n |designer =\n |first flight = 2009\n |introduction =  \n |retired =\n |number built = \n |status = Active\n |unit cost = \n |primary user = [[Brazilian Navy]]  \n |more users =  \n |variants with their own articles =  Carcara II\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Carcar\u00e1''' is a Brazilian light weight [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] designed to be transported by a single soldier. The soldier's height allows takeoff and landing in restricted areas where other aircraft are unable to operate. It is designed to be used in any theater even if it is without roads or paths, or surrounded by obstacles.\n\nIt is designed to be used by [[Brazilian Marine Corps]] infantry in real-time reconnaissance.\n \n==Characteristics==\n\nThe Carcar\u00e1 was ordered by the [[Brazilian Navy]] to equip an infantry [[Brazilian Marine Corps|Marine Corps]]. The Navy wanted a [[UAV]] with[[Stealth technology | stealth]] features which was lightweight, flexible and resistant. The Carcar\u00e1 has a low acoustic signature, can be controlled by a single soldier and can gather telemetry data. It can be programmed to follow a target automatically. To the naked eye while in the air, it is very similar to a [[Caracara (subfamily)|caracara]].\n\n==Specifications==\n*Wingspan: 160&nbsp;cm\n*Operating speed: 40&nbsp;km / h\n*Takeoff: manual or catapult\n*Recovery: \"deep stall\"\n*Autonomy: 60 to 95 minutes\n*Payload: mobile camera with zoom, or Infra-red sensor\n\n==External links==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20091202073024/http://www.uav.com.br/carcara.htm\n* http://www.defesanet.com.br/01_lz/laad2009/imagens/mb/carcara_vant.jpg\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carcara Uav}}\n[[Category:2000s Brazilian military aircraft]]\n[[Category:Unmanned aerial vehicles of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Unmanned military aircraft of Brazil]]\n\n{{UAV-stub}}\n{{aero-2000s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:fixed layout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carcara_UAV"}
{"title_page": "Louise Burfitt-Dons", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Louise Burfitt-Dons\n| image       = Louise Burfitt-Dons, 2011 (cropped).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Louise Olivian Byres\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Magwa|Magwa, Great Burgan, Kuwait]]\n| nationality = British\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Activism\n| occupation  = Public speaker; author\n| spouse      = {{Marriage|Donald Burfitt-Dons|1982}}\n| children    = Brooke, Arabella\n| website     = {{URL|www.louiseburfittdons.com}}\n}}\n'''Louise Burfitt-Dons''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSA}} (n\u00e9e Byres; born 22 October 1953) is a British novelist, humanitarian, and  former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate.\n\nBurfitt-Dons is best known for her [[Bullying#Anti-bullying movement|anti-bullying]] work as the founder of the charity [[Act Against Bullying]] and co-founder of [[Kindness Day UK]].\n\n==Early years and family==\nLouise Olivian Byres was born to Olive and Ian Byres in a small desert hospital at Magwa, in the [[Great Burgan|Burgan]] district just south of Kuwait City. Her father worked for [[Kuwait Oil Company]] and her mother ran a kindergarten. She had an elder brother, Laurence. She attended the Anglo-American School in Kuwait, and later [[The Hertfordshire and Essex High School]] and [[Ashford School|the Ashford School for Girls]] in Kent. Burfitt-Dons' father died of cancer when she was 26. During his illness she obtained a [[liquor licence]] and took over the running of The White Horse in [[East Bergholt]] so she could care for him.{{clarify|date=November 2013}}{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nBurfitt-Dons has two daughters, [[Brooke Burfitt]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Impact of extra tropic cyclones in Europe on Insurance Industry - Transcript of keynote speech by Donald Burfitt-Dons|publisher=The Global Warming Alliance|url=http://www.globalwarmingalliance.com/insurance_implications.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711101642/http://www.globalwarmingalliance.com/insurance_implications.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 July 2011|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brooke appeals for residents' votes to help get her to semi final|publisher=ChiswickW4.com|date=14 October 2009|url=http://www.chiswickw4.com/info/conceleb195.htm|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Brooke Burfitt-Dons|publisher=brookeburfitt.com|url=http://www.brookeburfitt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=49&Itemid=27|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref> and Arabella (b. 1992),<ref>{{cite web|title=Arabella Burfitt-Dons - University of Nottingham - Civil Engineering|publisher=Autodesk|url=http://students.autodesk.com/?nd=m_student_profile&account_id=1838282&return_nd=m_university_detail|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref> by her pilot husband Donald Burfitt-Dons, a New Zealander whom she met and married in London in 1982 while he was on an overseas basing with [[Qantas]]. The couple lived in Australia between 1982\u201393 where Louise worked as an actress and wrote plays for the Sydney stage. She co-starred in a dinner theatre show with [[Andrew Harwood (television host)|Andrew Harwood]] in 1988.   She lives in [[Chiswick]], [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RAF Air Squadron Trophy Competition|work=News|publisher=The Lady Eleanor Holles School|url=http://www.lehs.org.uk/srnews/RAF_Air_Squadron_Trophy_Competition.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119173244/http://www.lehs.org.uk/srnews/RAF_Air_Squadron_Trophy_Competition.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 January 2015|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Brooke Burfitt-Dons|work=Bio|publisher=Brooke Burfitt-Dons|url=http://www.brookeburfittdons.com/index.php?view=article&catid=34%3Acelebinterviews&id=49%3Ahayley&format=pdf&option=com_content&Itemid=41|format=PDF|accessdate=1 June 2010}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Social commentary==\nLouise has appeared on [[Sky News]], ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[Channel Four News]]'', [[ITV News London]], [[ITN]], ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'' and Talk Radio Europe, [[BBC Surrey]] and [[BBC Sussex]], [[BBC Oxford]], [[LBC]], ''[[PM (BBC Radio 4)|PM]]'', [[Talkradio]] ''[[The World Tonight]]''. She has written on social affairs and political issues for a range of blogs including [[Conservative Home]] and  [[Conservative Way Forward]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conwayfor.org/louise_burfitt_dons_why_it_s_time_for_a_moderate_form_of_feminism_to_assert_itself|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: Why it\u2019s time for a moderate form of feminism to assert itself|work=conwayfor.org|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> She is a regular news reviewer on the [[Ian Collins (radio presenter)|Ian Collins]] show ''Roundtable'' on [[LBC]].\n\n==Boosting Britain==\nIn 2012, after visiting a range of different businesses,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Business/Business-News/Campaigner-visits-Dunmow-business-30082012.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227224837/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Business/Business-News/Campaigner-visits-Dunmow-business-30082012.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 February 2014|title=Campaigner visits Dunmow business|date=30 August 2012|work=hertsandessexobserver.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> she set up an online initiative named 'Boosting Britain' to encourage and promote new ideas and companies which were helping Britain. It covered [[infrastructure]], [[defence industry]], education as well as [[motivational]] factors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boostingbritain.org/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=19 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225174020/http://boostingbritain.org/index.htm |archivedate=25 February 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"conservativehome.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2014/02/from-louiseburfdons-to-boost-britains-quota-of-engineers-why-not-take-a-page-from-germanys-book.html|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: To boost Britain\u2019s quota of engineers, why not take a page from Germany\u2019s book? - Conservative Home|work=conservativehome.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> She has suggested more honorary titles for engineers would help to bolster their image and help with the skills shortage<ref name=\"conservativehome.com\"/> As of 2017, the website was unregistered and not connecting.\n\n==Campaigning==\nSince setting up [[Act Against Bullying]], Burfitt-Dons has been outspoken on the ill-effects of [[tribalism]] in society as a speaker and writer. She has advocated that tribalism is on the increase and has been taking effect in all forms of modern society leading to social unrest. Feeling the need to express what the public was confiding in her she designed a range of campaigns to promote human dignity and individuality in modern society.\n\nShe designed the \"Cool to Be Kind\" Campaign in 2000; two years later she founded the National Decency Campaign in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eparenting.co.uk/parenting/nationaldecencycampaign.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=13 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010140128/http://www.eparenting.co.uk/parenting/nationaldecencycampaign.shtml |archivedate=10 October 2006 }}</ref> and, in 2006, the \"Grade Not Degrade\" campaign. ''[[The Scotsman]]'' quoted her as suggesting ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 5 (UK)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' was legitimising the growing trend of bullying behaviour in classrooms around the country.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hello |url=http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment.cfm?id=116102007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209012759/http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment.cfm?id=116102007 |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 February 2007 |title=Violent soap operas and bullying behaviour on television shows harm children - The Scotsman |website=News.scotsman.com |date=2007-01-23 |accessdate=2016-06-17 }}</ref> She spoke at the Conservative Women's Organisation Forum <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativewomen.org.uk/article.asp?art_id=63 |title=CWO News :: CWO Forum - Cyber Bullying |website=Conservativewomen.org.uk |date=2007-06-28 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> at the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] on [[cyber bullying]] claiming that today \"children have to be as savvy as celebrities but without the pr support\". In response to the growing trend of internet abuse she designed the CyberKind Campaign, which was launched on [[Remembrance Day]] (11 November) 2009.\n\nBurfitt-Dons founded the [[UK Kindness Movement]] and co-founder of [[Kindness Day UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2010/11/12/kindness-day-uk-launches-13-november_n_7414126.html|title=Kindness Day UK Launches 13 November|date=12 November 2010|work=huffingtonpost.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.responsesource.com/releases/rel_display.php?relid=60351|title=Tens of Thousands take up Kindness Across the UK|work=responsesource.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> She appeared on [[BBC Breakfast]] on the first Kindness Day UK on 13 November 2010 alongside [[Kathy Lette]] who claimed that English people were condescending and unfriendly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=70ymutgb1k0 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101222157/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=70ymutgb1k0 |archivedate=1 November 2013 }}</ref>  In 2007 she began campaigning on global warming and has said that \"climate change may be the ultimate issue that unites us all\". {{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2006 she was nominated as an Angel Hero for [[The My Hero Project]]. In May 2009 she was invited to become a [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] in recognition of her work with children as well as to acknowledge her efforts as a campaigner and speaker on humanitarian and environmental issues. {{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Global warming==\nBurfitt-Dons co-founded the Global Warming Alliance which was set up in January 2006 to find solutions to the crisis. On 2 December 2008, she launched the Global Warming Hotspot <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/globalwarminghotspot |title=Globalwarminghotspot : List of videos |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> channel on [[YouTube]]. She spearheaded the international Hot Women Campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecoearth.info/links/Air/Climate/Policy_Actors/Non-Governmental_Organizations/welcome.asp|title=EcoEarth.Info Environment Links: Air/Climate/Policy Actors/Non-Governmental Organizations|date=21 April 2012|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421213159/http://www.ecoearth.info/links/Air/Climate/Policy_Actors/Non-Governmental_Organizations/welcome.asp|archivedate=21 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which encouraged women to become more active in [[climate change]] issues and reduce carbon emissions and significantly raised awareness of the differences between male and female thinking on the issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.edu/worldedu_posts/genders-climate-change-women-men-accept-global-warming |title=How the genders think about climate change: Women more likely than men to accept global warming - World leading higher education information and services |website=World.edu |date=2010-09-26 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> ''The Scotsman'' quoted Burfitt-Dons' claims that \"the relentless rise in CO2 emissions is incrementally raising planetary temperatures, increasing water vapour in the atmosphere with a commensurate rise in rainfall, and ever stronger wind patterns randomly occurring across the globe.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Craig Brown |url=http://www.scotsman.com/the-scotsman/environment/darling_buds_of_may_april_more_like_1_1962484 |title=Darling buds of May? April more like |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |date=2011-11-12 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==Feminism==\nBurfitt-Dons got involved with women's issues because of her charity work as a motivational speaker and mentor. In October 2009 she was part of the freshers feminist debate at [[Cambridge University]] <ref>[http://cambridgetab.co.uk/featured/currie-tikkad-off-2]  {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131105231031/http://cambridgetab.co.uk/featured/currie-tikkad-off-2 |date=5 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cambridgetab.co.uk/columnists/standing-up-for-sisterhood |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091101003448/http://cambridgetab.co.uk/columnists/standing-up-for-sisterhood/ |archivedate=1 November 2009 }}</ref> with ''[[Cosmopolitan Magazine]]'' editor Louise Court and [[Edwina Currie]]. Burfitt-Dons set up the [[Royal Society of Arts]]' Women's Speakers' Network whose mission is to \"raise women's profile in society by greater involvement in public speaking\". She chaired the launch event at the [[Institution of Mechanical Engineers]] on 9 November 2010 in a public debate entitled \"The Great Female Debate: Do Women Speak Too much or too little?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://belsizeconservatives.yourcllr.com/2010/10/26/do-women-speak-too-much-or-too-little |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131105231052/http://belsizeconservatives.yourcllr.com/2010/10/26/do-women-speak-too-much-or-too-little |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-11-05 |title=Do Women Speak Too Much Or Too Little? |website=Belsizeconservatives.yourcllr.com |date=2010-10-26 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> She believes that some feminist groups have hijacked and radicalised the equality movement and has catalysed a debate around feminism calling on more gender realism via her blog The Common Sense Feminist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecommonsensefeminist.wordpress.com|title=The Common Sense Feminist|work=wordpress.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2014/01/from-motivatingwoman-right-wing-feminism.html|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: The successes and failures of feminism - Conservative Home|work=conservativehome.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> Her work on feminism includes the book ''Moderating Feminism:The Past The Now and What Comes Next'' (2016).\n\n==Politics==\nIn September 2014 she was selected to fight the 2015 General Election for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in  [[Nottingham North]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Prospective_Parliamentary_Candidates/Burfitt-Dons.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=1 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119183632/https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Prospective_Parliamentary_Candidates/Burfitt-Dons.aspx |archivedate=19 January 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2013/05/louise.html |title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: It\u2019s time for the Tories to target a new type of female voter |website=Conservativehome.blogs.com |date=2013-05-30 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hucknalldispatch.co.uk/news/local/mp-slams-govt-fail-on-employment-1-6907825|title=MP slams Govt fail on employment|work=hucknalldispatch.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Robinson|first1=Dan|title=Nottingham MP calls for 'unfair' tax on sixth form colleges to be scrapped to help Bilborough youngsters  |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Nottingham-MP-calls-unfair-tax-sixth-form/story-26016610-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221144018/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Nottingham-MP-calls-unfair-tax-sixth-form/story-26016610-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-02-21|website=Nottingham Post}}</ref> She clashed with the incumbent MP [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]] over his criticism of small businesses in Nottingham North<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cunningham|first1=Tim|title=Politicians Clash over Minimum Pay|url=http://www.hucknalldispatch.co.uk/news/local/politicians-clash-over-minimum-pay-1-7055838|website=Hucknall Today|accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref> She has challenged [[Nottingham City Council]] over its Workplace Parking Levy policy as `short term thinking' at its worse and suggested it was a political decision rather than an economic one.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: Is the WPL an economic or a political issue?|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-WPL-economic-political-issue/story-26122053-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402134421/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-WPL-economic-political-issue/story-26122053-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 April 2015|website=Nottingham Post|publisher=Nottingham Post Online|accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>  Nottingham was the first City Council to introduce a Workplace Parking Levy in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=Online Voting Is Not Secure Enough|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-Online-voting-quick-easy/story-26290207-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150428215207/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-Online-voting-quick-easy/story-26290207-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 April 2015|website=Nottingham Post|publisher=Nottingham Post|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Publications, novels and plays==\n*''The Missing Activist'' (August 2018 )<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=The Missing Activist|date=7 August 2018|publisher=New Century Digibooks|isbn=9780953852291}}</ref>\n*''Moderating Feminism'' (August 2016 )<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=Moderating Feminism|date=29 July 2016|publisher=New Century Digibooks|isbn=9780953852277}}</ref>\n*''The Counsellor'' (October 2000)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=The Counsellor|year=2000|publisher=New Century|isbn=9780953852215}}</ref> \n*''Painkillers'' (June 2001)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=Painkillers|year=June 2001|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852239}}</ref> \n*''Act Against Bullying'' (August 2002)<ref>{{cite book|last=Burfitt-Dons|first=Louise|title=Act Against Bullying|year=2002|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852253}}</ref> \n*''A Christmas Riddle'' (June 2000)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=A Christmas Riddle|year=2000|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852208}}</ref> \n*''Valentine Card'' (June 2001)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=The Valentine Card|year=2001|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852222}}</ref> \n*''How to Catch A Man'' (September 1991)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=How to Catch A Man|year=1991|publisher=Ashley Books|isbn=978-0879493479}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.louiseburfittdons.com/ Louise Burfitt-Dons]\n*[http://thecommonsensefeminist.wordpress.com/ The Common Sense Feminist]\n\n{{Bullying}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burfitt-Dons, Louise}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Green thinkers]]\n[[Category:British environmentalists]]\n[[Category:British women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:British humanitarians]]\n[[Category:English feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Sustainability advocates]]\n[[Category:English motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Hertfordshire and Essex High School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ashford School]]\n[[Category:Anti-bullying activists]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Academics and writers on bullying]]\n[[Category:British women activists]]\n[[Category:English activists]]\n[[Category:English women activists]]\n[[Category:British activists]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Women bloggers]]\n[[Category:Crime Writers' Association]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:English thriller writers]]\n[[Category:English crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Women thriller writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Louise Burfitt-Dons\n| image       = Louise Burfitt-Dons, 2011 (cropped).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Louise Olivian Byres\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Magwa|Magwa, Great Burgan, Kuwait]]\n| nationality = British\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Activism\n| occupation  = Public speaker; author\n| spouse      = {{Marriage|Donald Burfitt-Dons|1982}}\n| children    = Brooke, Arabella\n| website     = {{URL|www.louiseburfittdons.com}}\n}}\n'''Louise Burfitt-Dons''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSA}} (n\u00e9e Byres; born 22 October 1953) is a British novelist, humanitarian, and  former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate.\n\nBurfitt-Dons is best known for her [[Bullying#Anti-bullying movement|anti-bullying]] work as the founder of the charity [[Act Against Bullying]] and co-founder of [[Kindness Day UK]].\n\n==Early years and family==\nLouise Olivian Byres was born to Olive and Ian Byres in a small desert hospital at Magwa, in the [[Great Burgan|Burgan]] district just south of Kuwait City. Her father worked for [[Kuwait Oil Company]] and her mother ran a kindergarten. She had an elder brother, Laurence. She attended the Anglo-American School in Kuwait, and later [[The Hertfordshire and Essex High School]] and [[Ashford School|the Ashford School for Girls]] in Kent. Burfitt-Dons' father died of cancer when she was 26. During his illness she obtained a [[liquor licence]] and took over the running of The White Horse in [[East Bergholt]] so she could care for him.{{clarify|date=November 2013}}{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nBurfitt-Dons has two daughters, [[Brooke Burfitt]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Impact of extra tropic cyclones in Europe on Insurance Industry - Transcript of keynote speech by Donald Burfitt-Dons|publisher=The Global Warming Alliance|url=http://www.globalwarmingalliance.com/insurance_implications.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711101642/http://www.globalwarmingalliance.com/insurance_implications.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 July 2011|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brooke appeals for residents' votes to help get her to semi final|publisher=ChiswickW4.com|date=14 October 2009|url=http://www.chiswickw4.com/info/conceleb195.htm|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Brooke Burfitt-Dons|publisher=brookeburfitt.com|url=http://www.brookeburfitt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=49&Itemid=27|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref> and Arabella (b. 1992),<ref>{{cite web|title=Arabella Burfitt-Dons - University of Nottingham - Civil Engineering|publisher=Autodesk|url=http://students.autodesk.com/?nd=m_student_profile&account_id=1838282&return_nd=m_university_detail|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref> by her pilot husband Donald Burfitt-Dons, a New Zealander whom she met and married in London in 1982 while he was on an overseas basing with [[Qantas]]. The couple lived in Australia between 1982\u201393 where Louise worked as an actress and wrote plays for the Sydney stage. She co-starred in a dinner theatre show with [[Andrew Harwood (television host)|Andrew Harwood]] in 1988.   She lives in [[Chiswick]], [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RAF Air Squadron Trophy Competition|work=News|publisher=The Lady Eleanor Holles School|url=http://www.lehs.org.uk/srnews/RAF_Air_Squadron_Trophy_Competition.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119173244/http://www.lehs.org.uk/srnews/RAF_Air_Squadron_Trophy_Competition.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 January 2015|accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Brooke Burfitt-Dons|work=Bio|publisher=Brooke Burfitt-Dons|url=http://www.brookeburfittdons.com/index.php?view=article&catid=34%3Acelebinterviews&id=49%3Ahayley&format=pdf&option=com_content&Itemid=41|format=PDF|accessdate=1 June 2010}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Social commentary==\nLouise has appeared on [[Sky News]], ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[Channel Four News]]'', [[ITV News London]], [[ITN]], ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'' and Talk Radio Europe, [[BBC Surrey]] and [[BBC Sussex]], [[BBC Oxford]], [[LBC]], ''[[PM (BBC Radio 4)|PM]]'', [[Talkradio]] ''[[The World Tonight]]''. She has written on social affairs and political issues for a range of blogs including [[Conservative Home]] and  [[Conservative Way Forward]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conwayfor.org/louise_burfitt_dons_why_it_s_time_for_a_moderate_form_of_feminism_to_assert_itself|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: Why it\u2019s time for a moderate form of feminism to assert itself|work=conwayfor.org|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> She is a regular news reviewer on the [[Ian Collins (radio presenter)|Ian Collins]] show ''Roundtable'' on [[LBC]].\n\n==Boosting Britain==\nIn 2012, after visiting a range of different businesses,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Business/Business-News/Campaigner-visits-Dunmow-business-30082012.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227224837/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Business/Business-News/Campaigner-visits-Dunmow-business-30082012.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 February 2014|title=Campaigner visits Dunmow business|date=30 August 2012|work=hertsandessexobserver.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> she set up an online initiative named 'Boosting Britain' to encourage and promote new ideas and companies which were helping Britain. It covered [[infrastructure]], [[defence industry]], education as well as [[motivational]] factors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boostingbritain.org/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=19 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225174020/http://boostingbritain.org/index.htm |archivedate=25 February 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"conservativehome.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2014/02/from-louiseburfdons-to-boost-britains-quota-of-engineers-why-not-take-a-page-from-germanys-book.html|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: To boost Britain\u2019s quota of engineers, why not take a page from Germany\u2019s book? - Conservative Home|work=conservativehome.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> She has suggested more honorary titles for engineers would help to bolster their image and help with the skills shortage<ref name=\"conservativehome.com\"/> As of 2017, the website was unregistered and not connecting.\n\n==Campaigning==\nSince setting up [[Act Against Bullying]], Burfitt-Dons has been outspoken on the ill-effects of [[tribalism]] in society as a speaker and writer. She has advocated that tribalism is on the increase and has been taking effect in all forms of modern society leading to social unrest. Feeling the need to express what the public was confiding in her she designed a range of campaigns to promote human dignity and individuality in modern society.\n\nShe designed the \"Cool to Be Kind\" Campaign in 2000; two years later she founded the National Decency Campaign in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eparenting.co.uk/parenting/nationaldecencycampaign.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=13 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010140128/http://www.eparenting.co.uk/parenting/nationaldecencycampaign.shtml |archivedate=10 October 2006 }}</ref> and, in 2006, the \"Grade Not Degrade\" campaign. ''[[The Scotsman]]'' quoted her as suggesting ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 5 (UK)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' was legitimising the growing trend of bullying behaviour in classrooms around the country.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hello |url=http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment.cfm?id=116102007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209012759/http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment.cfm?id=116102007 |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 February 2007 |title=Violent soap operas and bullying behaviour on television shows harm children - The Scotsman |website=News.scotsman.com |date=2007-01-23 |accessdate=2016-06-17 }}</ref> She spoke at the Conservative Women's Organisation Forum <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativewomen.org.uk/article.asp?art_id=63 |title=CWO News :: CWO Forum - Cyber Bullying |website=Conservativewomen.org.uk |date=2007-06-28 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> at the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] on [[cyber bullying]] claiming that today \"children have to be as savvy as celebrities but without the pr support\". In response to the growing trend of internet abuse she designed the CyberKind Campaign, which was launched on [[Remembrance Day]] (11 November) 2009.\n\nBurfitt-Dons founded the [[UK Kindness Movement]] and co-founder of [[Kindness Day UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2010/11/12/kindness-day-uk-launches-13-november_n_7414126.html|title=Kindness Day UK Launches 13 November|date=12 November 2010|work=huffingtonpost.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.responsesource.com/releases/rel_display.php?relid=60351|title=Tens of Thousands take up Kindness Across the UK|work=responsesource.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> She appeared on [[BBC Breakfast]] on the first Kindness Day UK on 13 November 2010 alongside [[Kathy Lette]] who claimed that English people were condescending and unfriendly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=70ymutgb1k0 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101222157/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=70ymutgb1k0 |archivedate=1 November 2013 }}</ref>  In 2007 she began campaigning on global warming and has said that \"climate change may be the ultimate issue that unites us all\". {{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2006 she was nominated as an Angel Hero for [[The My Hero Project]]. In May 2009 she was invited to become a [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] in recognition of her work with children as well as to acknowledge her efforts as a campaigner and speaker on humanitarian and environmental issues. {{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Global warming==\nBurfitt-Dons co-founded the Global Warming Alliance which was set up in January 2006 to find solutions to the crisis. On 2 December 2008, she launched the Global Warming Hotspot <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/globalwarminghotspot |title=Globalwarminghotspot : List of videos |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> channel on [[YouTube]]. She spearheaded the international Hot Women Campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecoearth.info/links/Air/Climate/Policy_Actors/Non-Governmental_Organizations/welcome.asp|title=EcoEarth.Info Environment Links: Air/Climate/Policy Actors/Non-Governmental Organizations|date=21 April 2012|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421213159/http://www.ecoearth.info/links/Air/Climate/Policy_Actors/Non-Governmental_Organizations/welcome.asp|archivedate=21 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which encouraged women to become more active in [[climate change]] issues and reduce carbon emissions and significantly raised awareness of the differences between male and female thinking on the issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.edu/worldedu_posts/genders-climate-change-women-men-accept-global-warming |title=How the genders think about climate change: Women more likely than men to accept global warming - World leading higher education information and services |website=World.edu |date=2010-09-26 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> ''The Scotsman'' quoted Burfitt-Dons' claims that \"the relentless rise in CO2 emissions is incrementally raising planetary temperatures, increasing water vapour in the atmosphere with a commensurate rise in rainfall, and ever stronger wind patterns randomly occurring across the globe.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Craig Brown |url=http://www.scotsman.com/the-scotsman/environment/darling_buds_of_may_april_more_like_1_1962484 |title=Darling buds of May? April more like |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |date=2011-11-12 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==Feminism==\nBurfitt-Dons got involved with women's issues because of her charity work as a motivational speaker and mentor. In October 2009 she was part of the freshers feminist debate at [[Cambridge University]] <ref>[http://cambridgetab.co.uk/featured/currie-tikkad-off-2]  {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131105231031/http://cambridgetab.co.uk/featured/currie-tikkad-off-2 |date=5 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cambridgetab.co.uk/columnists/standing-up-for-sisterhood |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091101003448/http://cambridgetab.co.uk/columnists/standing-up-for-sisterhood/ |archivedate=1 November 2009 }}</ref> with ''[[Cosmopolitan Magazine]]'' editor Louise Court and [[Edwina Currie]]. Burfitt-Dons set up the [[Royal Society of Arts]]' Women's Speakers' Network whose mission is to \"raise women's profile in society by greater involvement in public speaking\". She chaired the launch event at the [[Institution of Mechanical Engineers]] on 9 November 2010 in a public debate entitled \"The Great Female Debate: Do Women Speak Too much or too little?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://belsizeconservatives.yourcllr.com/2010/10/26/do-women-speak-too-much-or-too-little |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131105231052/http://belsizeconservatives.yourcllr.com/2010/10/26/do-women-speak-too-much-or-too-little |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-11-05 |title=Do Women Speak Too Much Or Too Little? |website=Belsizeconservatives.yourcllr.com |date=2010-10-26 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> She believes that some feminist groups have hijacked and radicalised the equality movement and has catalysed a debate around feminism calling on more gender realism via her blog The Common Sense Feminist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecommonsensefeminist.wordpress.com|title=The Common Sense Feminist|work=wordpress.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2014/01/from-motivatingwoman-right-wing-feminism.html|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: The successes and failures of feminism - Conservative Home|work=conservativehome.com|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> Her work on feminism includes the book ''Moderating Feminism:The Past The Now and What Comes Next'' (2016).\n\n==Politics==\nIn September 2014 she was selected to fight the 2015 General Election for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in  [[Nottingham North]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Prospective_Parliamentary_Candidates/Burfitt-Dons.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=1 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119183632/https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Prospective_Parliamentary_Candidates/Burfitt-Dons.aspx |archivedate=19 January 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2013/05/louise.html |title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: It\u2019s time for the Tories to target a new type of female voter |website=Conservativehome.blogs.com |date=2013-05-30 |accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hucknalldispatch.co.uk/news/local/mp-slams-govt-fail-on-employment-1-6907825|title=MP slams Govt fail on employment|work=hucknalldispatch.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Robinson|first1=Dan|title=Nottingham MP calls for 'unfair' tax on sixth form colleges to be scrapped to help Bilborough youngsters  |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Nottingham-MP-calls-unfair-tax-sixth-form/story-26016610-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221144018/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Nottingham-MP-calls-unfair-tax-sixth-form/story-26016610-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-02-21|website=Nottingham Post}}</ref> She clashed with the incumbent MP [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]] over his criticism of small businesses in Nottingham North<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cunningham|first1=Tim|title=Politicians Clash over Minimum Pay|url=http://www.hucknalldispatch.co.uk/news/local/politicians-clash-over-minimum-pay-1-7055838|website=Hucknall Today|accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref> She has challenged [[Nottingham City Council]] over its Workplace Parking Levy policy as `short term thinking' at its worse and suggested it was a political decision rather than an economic one.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=Louise Burfitt-Dons: Is the WPL an economic or a political issue?|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-WPL-economic-political-issue/story-26122053-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402134421/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-WPL-economic-political-issue/story-26122053-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 April 2015|website=Nottingham Post|publisher=Nottingham Post Online|accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>  Nottingham was the first City Council to introduce a Workplace Parking Levy in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=Online Voting Is Not Secure Enough|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-Online-voting-quick-easy/story-26290207-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150428215207/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Louise-Burfitt-Dons-Online-voting-quick-easy/story-26290207-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 April 2015|website=Nottingham Post|publisher=Nottingham Post|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Publications, novels and plays==\n*''The Missing Activist'' (August 2018 )<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=The Missing Activist|date=7 August 2018|publisher=New Century Digibooks|isbn=9780953852291}}</ref>\n*''Moderating Feminism'' (August 2016 )<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burfitt-Dons|first1=Louise|title=Moderating Feminism|date=29 July 2016|publisher=New Century Digibooks|isbn=9780953852277}}</ref>\n*''The Counsellor'' (October 2000)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=The Counsellor|year=2000|publisher=New Century|isbn=9780953852215}}</ref> \n*''Painkillers'' (June 2001)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=Painkillers|year=June 2001|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852239}}</ref> \n*''Act Against Bullying'' (August 2002)<ref>{{cite book|last=Burfitt-Dons|first=Louise|title=Act Against Bullying|year=2002|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852253}}</ref> \n*''A Christmas Riddle'' (June 2000)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=A Christmas Riddle|year=2000|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852208}}</ref> \n*''Valentine Card'' (June 2001)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=The Valentine Card|year=2001|publisher=New Century|isbn=978-0953852222}}</ref> \n*''How to Catch A Man'' (September 1991)<ref>{{cite book|last=Byres|first=Louise|title=How to Catch A Man|year=1991|publisher=Ashley Books|isbn=978-0879493479}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.louiseburfittdons.com/ Louise Burfitt-Dons]\n*[http://thecommonsensefeminist.wordpress.com/ The Common Sense Feminist]\n\n{{Bullying}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burfitt-Dons, Louise}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Green thinkers]]\n[[Category:British environmentalists]]\n[[Category:British women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:British humanitarians]]\n[[Category:English feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Sustainability advocates]]\n[[Category:English motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Hertfordshire and Essex High School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ashford School]]\n[[Category:Anti-bullying activists]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Academics and writers on bullying]]\n[[Category:British women activists]]\n[[Category:English activists]]\n[[Category:English women activists]]\n[[Category:British activists]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Women bloggers]]\n[[Category:Crime Writers' Association]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:English thriller writers]]\n[[Category:English crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Women thriller writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louise_Burfitt-Dons"}
{"title_page": "R (March) v Secretary of State for Health", "text_new": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = ''E'' v. Secretary of State for the Home Department |link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html |court = EWCA | division = Civ |year = 2004 |num = 49 |parallelcite = [2004] QB 1044 |para=51}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref name=\"Hynes1\">{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=9 |page=89 |access-date=2010-04-12 |quote=''The payments by the Irish Government were equally made without an admission of liability.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref>\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry. In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |page=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref> The sequence of events in Ireland were critical to this case. The Irish government had decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking ''ex gratia'' in nature, and they decided to do this before there was any finding of fault.<ref name=\"Hynes1\" />  It was the Westminster government\u2019s stance on this that propagated the error.\n\nThere are a number of conditions which need to be met in order for the court to intervene: \n{{bulleted list |There must be a demonstrable error of fact;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=511 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''But the claimant must demonstrate that (i) there is an error of fact;''}},</ref> |The error needs to be sufficiently established;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=35c99556-a759-44fe-b12f-94ba54b72469 |title= Quashing a decision on the basis of material error of fact |last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=30 April 2010 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> | The claimant and their legal advisors must not have been party to the error; | The error of fact needs to be \u2033material\u2033; that there could have been an alternative decision \u2033but for the error\u2033.<ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [53] | quote=''In my view, the error is material because a different decision might (I stress, might) have been made if the government had correctly focussed on, and grappled with, the compassionate basis of Irish payments, when considering in particular the passage at internal pages 90 \u2013 94 of Archer which underpins recommendation 6 (h).''}}</ref>}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "text_old": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = ''E'' v. Secretary of State for the Home Department |link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html |court = EWCA | division = Civ |year = 2004 |num = 49 |parallelcite = [2004] QB 1044 |para=51}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref name=\"Hynes1\">{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=9 |page=89 |access-date=2010-04-12 |quote=''The payments by the Irish Government were equally made without an admission of liability.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref>\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry. In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |page=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref> The sequence of events in Ireland were critical to this case. The Irish government had decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking ''ex gratia'' in nature, and they decided to do this before there was any finding of fault.<ref name=\"Hynes1\" />  It was the Westminster government\u2019s stance on this that propagated the error.\n\nThere are a number of conditions which need to be met in order for the court to intervene: \n{{bulleted list |There must be a demonstrable error of fact;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=511 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''But the claimant must demonstrate that (i) there is an error of fact;''}},</ref> |The error needs to be sufficiently established;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=35c99556-a759-44fe-b12f-94ba54b72469 |title= Quashing a decision on the basis of material error of fact |last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=30 April 2010 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> | The claimant and their legal advisors must not have been party to the error; | The error of fact needs to be \u2033material\u2033; that there could have been an alternative decision \u2033but for the error\u2033.}}<ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [53] | quote=''In my view, the error is material because a different decision might (I stress, might) have been made if the government had correctly focussed on, and grappled with, the compassionate basis of Irish payments, when considering in particular the passage at internal pages 90 \u2013 94 of Archer which underpins recommendation 6 (h).''}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMaterial error of fact:Moving bracket to include the reference in the final bullet point.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_(March)_v_Secretary_of_State_for_Health"}
